    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-25T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-25T07:00:00-05:00" n="735"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d735">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-25T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 25, 1942—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 25—12:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>309. Department’s 134, August 19, 9 p.m., and my 281, August 12, 1 p.m. I have
                    now received a copy of Casey’s letter to Catroux concerning elections which will
                    go by pouch. The sentence concerning the United States reads as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“As you are aware the recognition of the independence of both states by
                            Egypt and Iraq is likely to depend on elections being held <pb
                                facs="0635" n="623" xml:id="pg_623"/> and there is reason to believe
                            that the United States Government take a similar view.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gwynn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
